title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Single-Six Lightweight "Tri-color", 1950s Rare 1st single six ruger made
postcontent:
Ruger Single-Six Lightweight "Tri-color", Flat Latch made in 1950s This example represents the earliest type of Single-Six Lightweight-used but in great shape highly colectable-Tri-color, Flatgate, Black checkered hard rubber grips, alloy cylinder, 4-5/8‚Äù barrel.RUGER  OLD  MODEL  SINGLE-SIX ‚ÄúLIGHTWEIGHT‚Äù
PRODUCED  1956 - 1959
In 1956 Ruger introduced a ‚ÄúLightweight‚Äù version of its Single-Six revolver.  The first Lightweights had an alloy cylinder frame, alloy cylinder, alloy grip frame, and steel barrel.  All Lightweights had a  standard 4-5/8 inch barrel. The first guns weighed 23 ounces versus the 35 ounce weight of the standard 5-1/2 inch barrel Single-Six.  The guns are roll-marked on the cylinder frame just like the standard Single-Six model, the word Lightweight does not appear in the roll-mark.  The first production guns had a silver/gray anodized cylinder frame, black anodized grip frame, flat cartridge loading gate, blued barrel, and Black checkered hard rubber grips.  They also had a coating on the alloy cylinder, the coating was known as ‚ÄúMartin Hard Coat‚Äù.  It was a brown or dark golden color (sometimes appears greenish or another color).  These first guns became known to collectors as the ‚ÄúTri-color‚Äù Lightweight.

title: For Sale:  CZ-52 Pistol
postcontent:
I have for sale a mostly original non-refurbished CZ-52 pistol.
This gun is functionally sound and has displayed no mechanical deficiencies after 250 rounds of modern production ammo.

This pistol is chambered in 7.62x25 tokarev and was manufactured in 1954 as evidenced by the stampings on the frame. It does not have the markings stamped into the frame indicating it was ever rearsenaled in the 1970's, so it is in as close to original condition and configuration as they come. Most examples of these pistols were monkeyed around with in the rearsenaling programs in the 70's, i.e. having the original powdered phosphate finish stripped and a hot blued finish applied, original internal components replaced with newer parts, etc. If you look at most examples of this pistol being sold locally through backpage and armslist they have a blued finish indicating that they are rearsenals.

The changes to the gun are as follows:

For those of you who are unaware of the DDLES buffer tube adapter, the original Sig 556 SWAT came with a folding stock that was proprietary to the Sig rifle.  This meant that you could not change out the stock for something else.
